00:04:04.990 --> 00:04:06.320
of children being separated.

00:04:06.320 --> 00:04:08.710
Migrant children from Central
America being separated

00:04:08.710 --> 00:04:12.660
from their families I think
shook the country again

00:04:12.660 --> 00:04:15.880
and made us confront difficult
moral and ethical questions

00:04:15.880 --> 00:04:22.390
about the way we treat people,
our neighbors who come mostly

00:04:22.390 --> 00:04:24.230
looking for protection
in our country.

00:04:24.230 --> 00:04:27.580
And I think that's what I
wanted to talk more about.

00:04:27.580 --> 00:04:31.720
The issue of immigration is
obviously a polemic issue.

00:04:31.720 --> 00:04:33.934
But I think there's
an important statistic

00:04:33.934 --> 00:04:35.350
that we should
remember when we're

00:04:35.350 --> 00:04:38.770
trying to interpret what it
means in our country right now.

00:04:38.770 --> 00:04:42.550
Immigration is in the
top 10, if not five,

00:04:42.550 --> 00:04:45.040
political issues of the day.

00:04:45.040 --> 00:04:48.550
Yet strikingly, the
numbers of immigrants

00:04:48.550 --> 00:04:52.820
coming into our country
is at a 30-year low.

00:04:52.820 --> 00:04:54.820
So it's important
to reflect on what

00:04:54.820 --> 00:04:57.670
is the nature of
migration crisis,

00:04:57.670 --> 00:05:00.030
if it is that we have one here.

00:05:00.030 --> 00:05:02.860
And I think it's also important
to put it in context to what's

00:05:02.860 --> 00:05:04.630
happening globally.

00:05:04.630 --> 00:05:08.620
There are more people in the
world displaced by violence

00:05:08.620 --> 00:05:13.610
than even during World War II,
which was the previous record.

00:05:13.610 --> 00:05:16.160
So there is a significant
crisis globally

00:05:16.160 --> 00:05:18.340
in people fleeing their homes.

00:05:18.340 --> 00:05:20.440
Protection of crisis,
because oftentimes

00:05:20.440 --> 00:05:23.470
they flee their homes they
aren't finding the solutions

00:05:23.470 --> 00:05:25.340
that they're looking for.

00:05:25.340 --> 00:05:27.670
But in our country,
we can't say that we

00:05:27.670 --> 00:05:29.860
have that problem of numbers.

00:05:29.860 --> 00:05:33.100
We can't say that our
communities are being inundated

00:05:33.100 --> 00:05:36.700
by a wave of migration.

00:05:36.700 --> 00:05:39.790
Because statistically
that's not happening.

00:05:39.790 --> 00:05:42.100
If we do have a
crisis in our country,

00:05:42.100 --> 00:05:46.430
I would say it's a
crisis of response.

00:05:46.430 --> 00:05:50.770
What's changed about immigration
from Central America and Mexico

00:05:50.770 --> 00:05:53.680
to the United States
is the demographic.

00:05:53.680 --> 00:05:56.200
What we have now
is less the profile

00:05:56.200 --> 00:05:59.410
of an individual coming from
Central America or Mexico

00:05:59.410 --> 00:06:01.930
looking for a job
or temporary work.

00:06:01.930 --> 00:06:05.230
And now we're having to
deal with the arrival

00:06:05.230 --> 00:06:08.950
of entire families, mostly
from Central America,

00:06:08.950 --> 00:06:10.450
coming to the United States.

00:06:10.450 --> 00:06:12.580
And many of them
are fleeing directly

00:06:12.580 --> 00:06:14.740
threats of violence
and persecution,

00:06:14.740 --> 00:06:18.190
or indirectly struggling to
live in an environment of what

00:06:18.190 --> 00:06:20.800
we call generalized violence.

00:06:20.800 --> 00:06:23.950
And so that demographic
shift in immigration

00:06:23.950 --> 00:06:28.900
has been a significant
challenge because it

00:06:28.900 --> 00:06:31.870
raises important questions
about our responsibilities,

00:06:31.870 --> 00:06:33.670
or our government's
responsibilities,

00:06:33.670 --> 00:06:35.860
to these people who arrive.

00:06:35.860 --> 00:06:37.360
Have they arrived illegally?

00:06:37.360 --> 00:06:39.250
Are they criminals?

00:06:39.250 --> 00:06:40.810
How should we respond?

00:06:40.810 --> 00:06:42.790
And I think that's
one of the things that

00:06:42.790 --> 00:06:47.860
made the policy of separating
children from their family so

00:06:47.860 --> 00:06:50.020
shocking to many people.

00:06:50.020 --> 00:06:54.070
Because I think that
there's increasing awareness

00:06:54.070 --> 00:06:56.530
among people in
the United States

00:06:56.530 --> 00:06:59.530
that children aren't
here to steal our jobs

00:06:59.530 --> 00:07:02.470
or to cause problems
in our communities.

00:07:02.470 --> 00:07:05.440
Something is going
on in the region

00:07:05.440 --> 00:07:09.640
in Central America that's
moving entire families to uproot

00:07:09.640 --> 00:07:13.070
themselves at great risk
to themselves to cross

00:07:13.070 --> 00:07:17.050
a border with little expectation
that they would be received

00:07:17.050 --> 00:07:18.610
and given legal status.

00:07:18.610 --> 00:07:21.670
Something must be
compelling them to flee.

00:07:21.670 --> 00:07:25.360
And I want to talk a little bit
more about those conditions.

00:07:25.360 --> 00:07:30.430
This idea of the prospect of a
demographic shift of migrants

00:07:30.430 --> 00:07:33.190
means that we have to challenge
our traditional narrative

00:07:33.190 --> 00:07:35.405
about immigration in the
Mesoamerican migratory

00:07:35.405 --> 00:07:35.905
corridor.

00:07:38.470 --> 00:07:41.790
We've thought for decades
now that the primary profile

00:07:41.790 --> 00:07:45.510
of a migrant moving through
Mexico into the United States

00:07:45.510 --> 00:07:47.390
is an economic migrant.

00:07:47.390 --> 00:07:49.780
One looking for opportunity.

00:07:49.780 --> 00:07:52.180
And that's the nature
of what a migrant is.

00:07:52.180 --> 00:07:55.670
It's someone who's chosen to
leave their homes in search

00:07:55.670 --> 00:08:00.290
of a better opportunity or
other options, education,

00:08:00.290 --> 00:08:02.150
family unification.

00:08:02.150 --> 00:08:05.720
But when people are compelled
to flee, they act differently.

00:08:05.720 --> 00:08:07.880
Often times people
who are forced to flee

00:08:07.880 --> 00:08:10.930
don't even have a
destination necessarily.

00:08:10.930 --> 00:08:12.634
They're not moving
with a specific plan

00:08:12.634 --> 00:08:13.550
that they thought out.

00:08:13.550 --> 00:08:15.980
They're moving because they
were forced from their homes

00:08:15.980 --> 00:08:19.850
and are desperately
trying to find an option.

00:08:19.850 --> 00:08:22.640
And that's different
than when people

00:08:22.640 --> 00:08:25.940
are trying to look for
a better opportunity

00:08:25.940 --> 00:08:31.150
and having planned or chosen
to take on their immigration.

00:08:31.150 --> 00:08:33.620
And so in Central
America our work

00:08:33.620 --> 00:08:36.380
has focused primarily on
people who are internally

00:08:36.380 --> 00:08:38.000
displaced by violence.

00:08:38.000 --> 00:08:39.890
Meaning that one
of the patterns we

00:08:39.890 --> 00:08:42.470
see that's related
to migratory outflows

00:08:42.470 --> 00:08:47.600
or transnational
movements of people

00:08:47.600 --> 00:08:50.270
is that people who
are fleeing oftentimes

00:08:50.270 --> 00:08:53.240
use internal displacement
as a precursor

00:08:53.240 --> 00:08:56.450
to a transnational
migratory route.

00:08:56.450 --> 00:09:01.010
For example, the first step may
often be moving from one home

00:09:01.010 --> 00:09:01.580
to another.

00:09:01.580 --> 00:09:04.640
Or staying with a family
member in the country of origin

00:09:04.640 --> 00:09:07.850
as a first means of
trying to find protection.

00:09:07.850 --> 00:09:11.870
And when those people exhaust
the options for protection,

00:09:11.870 --> 00:09:14.690
even using family
resources or even at times

00:09:14.690 --> 00:09:17.120
trying to get the
state to assist them,

00:09:17.120 --> 00:09:19.610
then they make the
decision to cross a border.

00:09:19.610 --> 00:09:21.680
And that moment is
really important.

00:09:21.680 --> 00:09:24.200
Because when people
are still within

00:09:24.200 --> 00:09:27.650
their national boundaries
of the country of origin,

00:09:27.650 --> 00:09:29.600
the international
frameworks tell us

00:09:29.600 --> 00:09:31.190
that internally
displaced people are

00:09:31.190 --> 00:09:33.560
the primary responsibilities
of the state

00:09:33.560 --> 00:09:36.489
and the government of
the country of origin.

00:09:36.489 --> 00:09:38.530
But when they cross an
international border, when

00:09:38.530 --> 00:09:41.360
a person-- this is the language
of the Refugee Convention--

00:09:41.360 --> 00:09:43.550
is unable or unwilling
to avail themselves

00:09:43.550 --> 00:09:46.190
of the protection in
their country of origin,

00:09:46.190 --> 00:09:48.380
that responsibility to
protect is transferred

00:09:48.380 --> 00:09:50.430
onto the host country.

00:09:50.430 --> 00:09:52.940
And the idea is
that no human being

00:09:52.940 --> 00:09:55.100
can be denied a
place on planet Earth

00:09:55.100 --> 00:09:59.090
where they can live free from
persecution and violence.

00:09:59.090 --> 00:10:01.280
It's to say that
everyone should be

00:10:01.280 --> 00:10:03.620
able to find some
place on planet Earth

00:10:03.620 --> 00:10:08.340
where their rights and basic
protection can be guaranteed.

00:10:08.340 --> 00:10:11.570
And so when Central
Americans make that decision

00:10:11.570 --> 00:10:13.730
to cross an
international border,

00:10:13.730 --> 00:10:17.210
they aren't being often
recognized as refugees.

00:10:17.210 --> 00:10:22.010
They're being treated as
illegal or regular migrants.

00:10:22.010 --> 00:10:24.344
And that's a
problematic scenario

00:10:24.344 --> 00:10:25.760
because you have
tens of thousands

00:10:25.760 --> 00:10:32.390
of people moving across
borders seeking protection.

00:10:32.390 --> 00:10:35.300
And no state is able
to give it to them.

00:10:35.300 --> 00:10:37.550
It's almost like forcing
a group of people

00:10:37.550 --> 00:10:39.670
to live in the shadows.

00:10:39.670 --> 00:10:42.530
I call it one of the greatest
acts of privatization

00:10:42.530 --> 00:10:44.570
in our generation,
is the privatization

00:10:44.570 --> 00:10:47.070
of the responsibility
to protect,

00:10:47.070 --> 00:10:50.030
which is primarily among
states but has been privatized

00:10:50.030 --> 00:10:51.350
to the families.

00:10:51.350 --> 00:10:54.590
And families do
courageous and often crazy

00:10:54.590 --> 00:10:57.890
things to try and find ways to
get their members to safety.

00:10:57.890 --> 00:11:01.190
And when North Americans
ask, for example,

00:11:01.190 --> 00:11:03.770
how is it possible that
Central American parents send

00:11:03.770 --> 00:11:05.550
their children on a
company to our border?

00:11:05.550 --> 00:11:07.550
It's because they're
making those very difficult

00:11:07.550 --> 00:11:11.060
calculations about how they can
find safety for at least one

00:11:11.060 --> 00:11:13.020
of their members.

00:11:13.020 --> 00:11:15.380
And knowing that
the United States

00:11:15.380 --> 00:11:20.480
has made great efforts to deter
migration by using detention.

00:11:20.480 --> 00:11:23.260
Or cruel conditions
while in detention

00:11:23.260 --> 00:11:25.880
to send messages back to
Central American families

00:11:25.880 --> 00:11:28.100
about how they will
be received when

00:11:28.100 --> 00:11:29.510
they come to the United States.

00:11:29.510 --> 00:11:31.640
That doesn't deter
a family who's

00:11:31.640 --> 00:11:38.610
faced with death, torture, rape,
or persecution in their homes.

00:11:38.610 --> 00:11:42.140
And so in some ways
these strategies

00:11:42.140 --> 00:11:44.960
that are abusive to migrants
in our own countries

00:11:44.960 --> 00:11:47.270
are also failures
on a policy level

00:11:47.270 --> 00:11:51.500
because they fail to understand
what it means to flee and not

00:11:51.500 --> 00:11:53.990
just migrate for opportunities.

00:11:53.990 --> 00:11:57.700
Cristosal-- our work as a human
rights organization focuses,

00:11:57.700 --> 00:11:59.450
as you heard in the
video, on accompanying

00:11:59.450 --> 00:12:01.320
victims of violence.

00:12:01.320 --> 00:12:03.620
We're not necessarily
working on migration.

00:12:03.620 --> 00:12:05.180
We see migration
and displacement

00:12:05.180 --> 00:12:09.580
as a consequence of
failure to protect rights

00:12:09.580 --> 00:12:12.170
and of a situation of
generalized violence

00:12:12.170 --> 00:12:12.800
in the region.

00:12:12.800 --> 00:12:14.450
And just to give
you a sense of what

00:12:14.450 --> 00:12:20.730
I mean by that,
between 2005 and 2009

00:12:20.730 --> 00:12:22.970
El Salvador, for
example, per capita

00:12:22.970 --> 00:12:26.570
had a higher rate of
violent death than Iraq

00:12:26.570 --> 00:12:29.240
during the peak of
their armed conflict.

00:12:29.240 --> 00:12:31.730
There was an interesting
academic article written

00:12:31.730 --> 00:12:34.310
by a colleague who wrote--

00:12:34.310 --> 00:12:37.440
the title of his piece was "More
Deadly Than Armed Conflict."

00:12:37.440 --> 00:12:40.125
And he looked at homicide
rates in the Northern Triangle,

00:12:40.125 --> 00:12:42.600
El Salvador, Guatemala,
and Honduras,

00:12:42.600 --> 00:12:45.840
and compared those to combined
homicide and casualty rates

00:12:45.840 --> 00:12:50.490
in countries like Syria or Iraq
that have open-armed conflicts,

00:12:50.490 --> 00:12:52.920
more traditional
armed conflicts.

00:12:52.920 --> 00:12:54.719
And the outcome of
that analysis is

00:12:54.719 --> 00:12:56.760
that these are some of
the most violent countries

00:12:56.760 --> 00:13:01.800
in the world even taking into
account countries in open war.

00:13:01.800 --> 00:13:03.540
And so what you
have in El Salvador

00:13:03.540 --> 00:13:08.580
is a situation that isn't
necessarily a traditional war,

00:13:08.580 --> 00:13:11.490
but one that's generating
humanitarian consequences that

00:13:11.490 --> 00:13:15.730
are comparative to other
armed conflicts in the world.

00:13:15.730 --> 00:13:18.090
And that's something
that has been difficult

00:13:18.090 --> 00:13:21.640
not only to integrate into this
narrative about immigration.

00:13:21.640 --> 00:13:23.850
Then perhaps we have
a refugee crisis

00:13:23.850 --> 00:13:25.840
on the American continent.

00:13:25.840 --> 00:13:27.630
But it's been
difficult to integrate

00:13:27.630 --> 00:13:31.290
into the security approaches in
the countries of the Northern

00:13:31.290 --> 00:13:32.640
Triangle.

00:13:32.640 --> 00:13:36.360
And what the governments have
done in response to violence

00:13:36.360 --> 00:13:38.940
is to declare war on
criminal groups that

00:13:38.940 --> 00:13:41.790
are the primary perpetrators
of atrocities and acts

00:13:41.790 --> 00:13:44.220
of violence, so street gangs.

00:13:44.220 --> 00:13:48.150
Street gangs is a diminutive
way of talking about them

00:13:48.150 --> 00:13:50.220
because they have
capacities that generally

00:13:50.220 --> 00:13:52.710
go beyond what we understand
in the United States

00:13:52.710 --> 00:13:54.270
as a street gang.

00:13:54.270 --> 00:13:57.060
They control territories.

00:13:57.060 --> 00:13:59.670
They control many aspects
of the lives of the people

00:13:59.670 --> 00:14:03.030
who live in those territories,
like where they can work.

00:14:03.030 --> 00:14:05.640
How they can sell if
they have a store.

00:14:05.640 --> 00:14:07.440
Where they can go to school.

00:14:07.440 --> 00:14:09.600
Where you can get health care.

00:14:09.600 --> 00:14:13.860
We've seen cases
where grandchildren

00:14:13.860 --> 00:14:15.660
have gone to visit
their grandmothers

00:14:15.660 --> 00:14:18.270
and had to cross an invisible
boundary between one gang

00:14:18.270 --> 00:14:19.590
territory and the other.

00:14:19.590 --> 00:14:24.420
And that has led to violent
acts perpetrated against them

00:14:24.420 --> 00:14:27.914
in reprisals for having entered
into opposite gang territory

00:14:27.914 --> 00:14:30.080
even though those people
aren't members of the gang.

00:14:34.019 --> 00:14:36.060
The easiest way to understand
it is to compare it

00:14:36.060 --> 00:14:38.550
to the way dictators work.

00:14:38.550 --> 00:14:40.620
Dictators control countries.

00:14:40.620 --> 00:14:44.130
They control many aspects
of the lives of the people.

00:14:44.130 --> 00:14:45.960
And people try and
find ways to live

00:14:45.960 --> 00:14:48.810
within those countries
acquiescent often

00:14:48.810 --> 00:14:53.199
to criminal actions of the state
up until they can't, the point

00:14:53.199 --> 00:14:54.240
where they can't anymore.

00:14:54.240 --> 00:14:57.930
Let's say in Syria, well,
I no longer can do this.

00:14:57.930 --> 00:14:59.430
Maybe I'm going to protest.

00:14:59.430 --> 00:15:02.460
And as soon as you challenge the
authority of the dictatorship,

00:15:02.460 --> 00:15:06.030
the dictatorship responds
with persecution and violence

00:15:06.030 --> 00:15:10.470
against you the same way that
the gangs act in communities.

00:15:10.470 --> 00:15:15.140
Gangs will force community
member for pay extortion.

00:15:15.140 --> 00:15:19.830
They'll force young members of
families to join their ranks.

00:15:19.830 --> 00:15:24.310
They'll force women
to become sex slaves.

00:15:24.310 --> 00:15:26.460
We call them
[SPEAKING SPANISH],, forced

00:15:26.460 --> 00:15:28.440
girlfriends of gang members.

00:15:28.440 --> 00:15:34.380
And so homicide, disappearances,
sexual violence all

00:15:34.380 --> 00:15:37.770
become ways of exercising
control in these areas.

00:15:37.770 --> 00:15:39.810
And the state is
incapable of stopping

00:15:39.810 --> 00:15:44.190
that Incapable of holding
back criminal groups who

00:15:44.190 --> 00:15:48.480
are capable of violating
fundamental rights of citizens.

00:15:48.480 --> 00:15:52.200
And what they've done, the
states, is declare war on them.

00:15:52.200 --> 00:15:56.130
And in this war the state
has militarized certain parts

00:15:56.130 --> 00:15:58.710
of the country
and used primarily

00:15:58.710 --> 00:16:02.610
repressive and military means
to try and reduce violence.

00:16:02.610 --> 00:16:05.340
Abandoning the consequences
of that violence,

00:16:05.340 --> 00:16:08.190
meaning that the entire
security approach

00:16:08.190 --> 00:16:11.940
has been a militaristic one.

00:16:11.940 --> 00:16:15.870
And there are no programs to
assist victims of violence.

00:16:15.870 --> 00:16:18.900
So when families
do become victims

00:16:18.900 --> 00:16:23.340
the justice system, the police,
the social security networks,

00:16:23.340 --> 00:16:24.780
the women's
protection institutes,

00:16:24.780 --> 00:16:26.460
the children
protection institutes

00:16:26.460 --> 00:16:29.050
are unable to do
anything for them.

00:16:29.050 --> 00:16:30.720
And so when we
try and understand

00:16:30.720 --> 00:16:34.170
why Central Americans or people
from the Northern Triangle

00:16:34.170 --> 00:16:37.380
leave the region, primarily
it's because of commissions

00:16:37.380 --> 00:16:41.610
of violence by criminal groups,
gangs, death squads, narco

00:16:41.610 --> 00:16:43.020
trafficking groups.

00:16:43.020 --> 00:16:46.800
But also violence by
the state, the army,

00:16:46.800 --> 00:16:51.930
the police in the context
of a war on gangs.

00:16:51.930 --> 00:16:54.720
And then omissions, the
failure of the state

00:16:54.720 --> 00:16:58.140
to do anything to guarantee
their lives, to assist victims.

00:16:58.140 --> 00:17:01.350
And so our goal
as an organization

00:17:01.350 --> 00:17:06.869
is to provide victims with
a safe space and services

00:17:06.869 --> 00:17:09.160
to stabilize their lives.

00:17:09.160 --> 00:17:11.819
And in that sense, it's a
very humanitarian mission

00:17:11.819 --> 00:17:13.410
to try and save lives.

00:17:13.410 --> 00:17:16.890
But also use that assistance to
help people to see themselves

00:17:16.890 --> 00:17:18.720
as agents of change.

00:17:18.720 --> 00:17:22.260
To try and change and challenge
the security strategy.

00:17:22.260 --> 00:17:25.260
To try and build and strengthen
the national protection system

00:17:25.260 --> 00:17:29.220
so that other families who
are in similar situations

00:17:29.220 --> 00:17:33.120
won't suffer without
any recourse.

00:17:33.120 --> 00:17:38.500
And so I left on
your rows a poster,

00:17:38.500 --> 00:17:44.184
a little poster that we made
of a drawing and a poem.

00:17:44.184 --> 00:17:46.100
And I wanted to share
this as a story with you

00:17:46.100 --> 00:17:49.370
to highlight how
our programs work.

00:17:49.370 --> 00:17:55.040
This drawing was made by a young
girl in one of our safe houses.

00:17:55.040 --> 00:18:01.190
And this girl was a member
of a family of 30 people.

00:18:01.190 --> 00:18:03.650
And this family lived
in an area controlled

00:18:03.650 --> 00:18:07.700
by a gang on the outskirts of
the capital of El Salvador, San

00:18:07.700 --> 00:18:09.620
Salvador.

00:18:09.620 --> 00:18:13.280
And this gang came
one day to the family

00:18:13.280 --> 00:18:16.310
and raped two of their members.

00:18:16.310 --> 00:18:18.710
They gang raped two
members of this family

00:18:18.710 --> 00:18:23.180
and told the family that if
they reported the crimes,

00:18:23.180 --> 00:18:26.540
if they resisted the gang's
future demands that they

00:18:26.540 --> 00:18:28.670
would all be killed.

00:18:28.670 --> 00:18:31.790
And so when the family was
threatened and suffered

00:18:31.790 --> 00:18:35.390
these acts of violence they
displaced to another community

00:18:35.390 --> 00:18:37.570
in El Salvador.

00:18:37.570 --> 00:18:41.430
And while they were in hiding
in a house in another place,

00:18:41.430 --> 00:18:45.530
the military entered into
the community in an operation

00:18:45.530 --> 00:18:47.690
with the police in
which they began

00:18:47.690 --> 00:18:51.230
to detain many of the young
men in that community.

00:18:51.230 --> 00:18:54.110
But they entered into the home
where this family was in hiding

00:18:54.110 --> 00:18:55.220
and began to fire.

00:18:55.220 --> 00:18:57.900
And they killed the
matriarch of the family.

00:18:57.900 --> 00:19:00.230
And they told the family
members that if they

00:19:00.230 --> 00:19:03.140
reported this crime,
if they said anything,

00:19:03.140 --> 00:19:04.980
that they would all die.

00:19:04.980 --> 00:19:06.980
And that's when they
entered into our program

00:19:06.980 --> 00:19:10.760
where we were able to provide
safe house protection for them,

00:19:10.760 --> 00:19:13.640
humanitarian assistance,
legal assistance,

00:19:13.640 --> 00:19:17.660
psychosocial assistance, medical
assistance to try and stabilize

00:19:17.660 --> 00:19:18.740
the family.

00:19:18.740 --> 00:19:20.630
But in that process we
began to talk to them

00:19:20.630 --> 00:19:24.920
about their rights, helping
them see that the violence

00:19:24.920 --> 00:19:28.160
and displacement that they had
suffered isn't their fault.

00:19:28.160 --> 00:19:32.540
That it's part of a system,
a security strategy that's

00:19:32.540 --> 00:19:34.670
immanently violent.

00:19:34.670 --> 00:19:37.100
But also part of a
structural problem

00:19:37.100 --> 00:19:39.470
in which the state
or the society

00:19:39.470 --> 00:19:41.690
hasn't made a commitment
to protecting and assisting

00:19:41.690 --> 00:19:42.520
victims.

00:19:42.520 --> 00:19:45.110
But that there's something
that could be done about that.

00:19:45.110 --> 00:19:48.860
And we began to talk to them
about maybe reconsidering

00:19:48.860 --> 00:19:50.930
reporting what happened.

00:19:50.930 --> 00:19:52.820
And we mentioned
to them the option

00:19:52.820 --> 00:19:55.570
of doing what we call
strategic litigation.

00:19:55.570 --> 00:19:58.380
That in El Salvador there
is a special mechanism

00:19:58.380 --> 00:20:01.590
that in the case of violation
of constitutional rights,

00:20:01.590 --> 00:20:04.820
citizens can go directly to
the highest judicial authority,

00:20:04.820 --> 00:20:06.674
the Supreme Court.

00:20:06.674 --> 00:20:08.090
And we asked them
if they would be

00:20:08.090 --> 00:20:12.020
willing to make a claim to
the Supreme Court holding

00:20:12.020 --> 00:20:14.240
the Attorney General,
the Minister of Defense,

00:20:14.240 --> 00:20:16.520
the Minister of
Justice and Security,

00:20:16.520 --> 00:20:20.090
and the Salvadoran legislature
responsible for violating

00:20:20.090 --> 00:20:23.570
their constitutional rights
in failing to protect them.

00:20:23.570 --> 00:20:25.550
And they didn't really
even think about it

00:20:25.550 --> 00:20:26.940
very long at all.

00:20:26.940 --> 00:20:30.470
They said, we understand
what happened to us.

00:20:30.470 --> 00:20:33.830
And if we can do anything
so that other families don't

00:20:33.830 --> 00:20:36.170
suffer what we have,
then it's worth the risk

00:20:36.170 --> 00:20:38.540
of trying to seek justice.

00:20:38.540 --> 00:20:43.970
And so they gave our lawyers,
our legal team, legal powers.

00:20:43.970 --> 00:20:47.370
And we presented a claim to
the Salvadoran Supreme Court

00:20:47.370 --> 00:20:49.610
suing those people I
mentioned for violating

00:20:49.610 --> 00:20:51.710
constitutional rights.

00:20:51.710 --> 00:20:53.730
I know this sounds
a little bit boring.

00:20:53.730 --> 00:20:55.610
But to make the
long story short,

00:20:55.610 --> 00:20:57.840
on July 13th the Supreme
Court of El Salvador

00:20:57.840 --> 00:21:00.740
ruled in favor of the victims.

00:21:00.740 --> 00:21:02.450
They said that the
Salvadoran state

00:21:02.450 --> 00:21:04.850
has to recognize internal
displacement by violence

00:21:04.850 --> 00:21:07.310
and their responsibility
to protect victims.

00:21:07.310 --> 00:21:10.100
They gave the state
six months to create

00:21:10.100 --> 00:21:13.760
a legislative framework
to build policy proposals

00:21:13.760 --> 00:21:18.410
and make a budget priority for
programs in the national budget

00:21:18.410 --> 00:21:20.240
to assist victims.

00:21:20.240 --> 00:21:24.560
And so we moved quickly
with the family.

00:21:24.560 --> 00:21:26.780
They authorized
us to draft a law

00:21:26.780 --> 00:21:30.020
and present it to the
Salvadoran legislature about two

00:21:30.020 --> 00:21:31.070
weeks ago.

00:21:31.070 --> 00:21:35.270
A special law to build a
national response to assist

00:21:35.270 --> 00:21:37.340
internally displaced people.

00:21:37.340 --> 00:21:39.860
And the law, when
we presented it

00:21:39.860 --> 00:21:43.820
to the Security Committee
of the legislator,

00:21:43.820 --> 00:21:47.450
the President took it directly
to the legislative assembly

00:21:47.450 --> 00:21:49.910
and asked for a streamlined
legislative process.

00:21:49.910 --> 00:21:52.440
And we needed 41 votes
for it to be admitted.

00:21:52.440 --> 00:21:56.960
And we got 44 on
the first round.

00:21:56.960 --> 00:22:00.560
And so now the law is being
assessed at the legal offices,

00:22:00.560 --> 00:22:01.580
all the ministries.

00:22:01.580 --> 00:22:02.900
And it's moving forward.

00:22:02.900 --> 00:22:05.300
So we have this
unbelievable opportunity.

00:22:05.300 --> 00:22:08.270
We're working with one case
with, as we said in the video,

00:22:08.270 --> 00:22:10.190
with one family.

00:22:10.190 --> 00:22:14.240
To safeguard their lives
we're now in a position

00:22:14.240 --> 00:22:17.450
to design the first
national response

00:22:17.450 --> 00:22:20.690
to internal displacement by
violence in Central America.

00:22:20.690 --> 00:22:22.100
And that's in El
Salvador, but we

00:22:22.100 --> 00:22:25.520
think that that model can
be used to also respond

00:22:25.520 --> 00:22:27.620
in Guatemala and Honduras.

00:22:27.620 --> 00:22:31.550
So it's a great privilege
of ours in the organization

00:22:31.550 --> 00:22:34.002
to be able to work
directly with victims

00:22:34.002 --> 00:22:35.210
and safeguarding their lives.

00:22:35.210 --> 00:22:38.840
But also be a part of expanding
protection for human rights

00:22:38.840 --> 00:22:41.120
to an entire
population of people.

00:22:41.120 --> 00:22:45.930
And designing also the national
response to this great problem

00:22:45.930 --> 00:22:49.930
affecting our region.

00:22:49.930 --> 00:22:51.810
So that's a success story.

00:22:51.810 --> 00:22:52.930
We're very happy.

00:22:52.930 --> 00:22:56.590
The poem I wanted to
draw your attention to,

00:22:56.590 --> 00:22:59.550
we translated at the
bottom of the poster.

00:22:59.550 --> 00:23:04.230
The drawing, we debated
whether this was something

00:23:04.230 --> 00:23:05.509
that's inspirational or not.

00:23:05.509 --> 00:23:07.550
But in the end, I think
it's quite inspirational.

00:23:07.550 --> 00:23:09.960
You can see in the
drawing that there's

00:23:09.960 --> 00:23:16.920
a caged bird in the mouth of the
girl, something that reminds us

00:23:16.920 --> 00:23:18.870
of the slogan that
many people see

00:23:18.870 --> 00:23:20.370
on the walls in the communities.

00:23:20.370 --> 00:23:24.330
It is see, here, and shut up.

00:23:24.330 --> 00:23:26.120
That's how you stay safe.

00:23:26.120 --> 00:23:29.610
And this is, as you can
imagine, a girl writing

00:23:29.610 --> 00:23:30.950
in a clandestine safe house.

00:23:30.950 --> 00:23:34.820
She writes this poem and
it is called "Sadness."

00:23:34.820 --> 00:23:38.430
It says, "if I am
free, I will be happy.

00:23:38.430 --> 00:23:41.890
I am the light that
illuminates in all places.

00:23:41.890 --> 00:23:45.420
I am your refuge and
I am your happiness."

00:23:45.420 --> 00:23:48.840
And I think the poem in
itself has its own merits.

00:23:48.840 --> 00:23:52.760
But when I think of how the
courage of her and her family

00:23:52.760 --> 00:23:57.120
in seeking justice and the
impact that potentially

00:23:57.120 --> 00:24:00.040
could have on so many
other people and families,

00:24:00.040 --> 00:24:01.260
I think that she's right.

00:24:01.260 --> 00:24:05.850
That she is the light and the
refuge for many in her hope.

00:24:05.850 --> 00:24:08.970
And if you like, you can
take these posters with you

00:24:08.970 --> 00:24:12.186
to share the story
with other people.

00:24:12.186 --> 00:24:15.206
I wanted to just
maybe close by sharing

00:24:15.206 --> 00:24:16.830
a little bit of a
reflection that we've

00:24:16.830 --> 00:24:19.380
been making about our work.

00:24:19.380 --> 00:24:22.740
Kathy mentioned that part
of our commitment to working

00:24:22.740 --> 00:24:25.440
with victims in Central
America has led us also

00:24:25.440 --> 00:24:29.980
to representing the victims
of the El Mazote Massacre.

00:24:29.980 --> 00:24:33.300
El Mazote is the
largest massacre

00:24:33.300 --> 00:24:38.580
perpetrated in the Western
hemisphere in modern times.

00:24:38.580 --> 00:24:41.010
In 1980, the Salvadoran
military entered

00:24:41.010 --> 00:24:43.320
into the village of El
Mazote and slaughtered

00:24:43.320 --> 00:24:44.500
over 1,000 people.

00:24:44.500 --> 00:24:46.950
Most of them were children.

00:24:46.950 --> 00:24:50.180
Today, Cristosal, as
a private plaintiff,

00:24:50.180 --> 00:24:53.010
is prosecuting the
Minister of Defense

00:24:53.010 --> 00:24:56.490
and the Salvadoran Military
High Command, the people who

00:24:56.490 --> 00:25:01.750
were the architects of the war
strategy from 1980 to 1984.

00:25:01.750 --> 00:25:05.220
And that war strategy was one
in which the military decided

00:25:05.220 --> 00:25:09.750
to exterminate all people who
lived in areas where there was

00:25:09.750 --> 00:25:13.330
a presence of insurgent groups.

00:25:13.330 --> 00:25:15.190
And one of the
things that we talk

00:25:15.190 --> 00:25:17.760
about when we talk about these
types of cases in which we're

00:25:17.760 --> 00:25:20.160
trying war criminals, or
trying people for crimes

00:25:20.160 --> 00:25:23.100
against humanity,
is that we don't

00:25:23.100 --> 00:25:28.750
believe that in successfully
prosecuting this case

00:25:28.750 --> 00:25:32.850
we will stop war crimes from
ever happening ever again.

00:25:32.850 --> 00:25:35.610
But what we do think makes
this struggle worthwhile,

00:25:35.610 --> 00:25:39.630
beyond the victim's right
to truth and justice,

00:25:39.630 --> 00:25:41.850
is that we have the
opportunity to challenge

00:25:41.850 --> 00:25:44.070
the assumption of impunity.

00:25:44.070 --> 00:25:47.220
That is the idea
that powerful people

00:25:47.220 --> 00:25:50.640
can do what they like
with weaker people

00:25:50.640 --> 00:25:52.050
simply because they can.

00:25:52.050 --> 00:25:54.330
And there will be no
consequences for it.

00:25:54.330 --> 00:25:56.340
That's one of the
dynamics of dictatorship

00:25:56.340 --> 00:25:58.470
and authoritarianism,
is this idea

00:25:58.470 --> 00:26:01.530
that I can do what I like
simply because I'm powerful.

00:26:01.530 --> 00:26:05.370
And I can do whatever I
like with whomever I like.

00:26:05.370 --> 00:26:08.250
And when we look
at those patterns,

00:26:08.250 --> 00:26:11.250
sometimes that impunity
manifests itself

00:26:11.250 --> 00:26:13.950
in atrocities like the
El Mazote Massacre.

00:26:13.950 --> 00:26:15.630
And sometimes it
manifests itself

00:26:15.630 --> 00:26:18.360
in simple corruption,
the idea that because I'm

00:26:18.360 --> 00:26:20.490
powerful I can do what I
like with the resources

00:26:20.490 --> 00:26:22.930
of the state, for example.

00:26:22.930 --> 00:26:26.550
And so this legacy in
Central America of violence,

00:26:26.550 --> 00:26:29.010
of abandonment of the
victims, and of corruption

00:26:29.010 --> 00:26:32.130
is linked to a historic
legacy of impunity.

00:26:32.130 --> 00:26:35.590
And so when we are prosecuting
the war crimes committed

00:26:35.590 --> 00:26:38.200
during the Salvadoran
Civil War 30 years ago,

00:26:38.200 --> 00:26:40.920
we think there's a direct
connection with our work

00:26:40.920 --> 00:26:42.224
with victims today.

00:26:42.224 --> 00:26:43.890
And we also think
that there's something

00:26:43.890 --> 00:26:47.100
important to be said in the
world about the assumption

00:26:47.100 --> 00:26:48.115
of impunity.

00:26:48.115 --> 00:26:49.890
When we look around
at our region,

00:26:49.890 --> 00:26:51.510
and we look around
at the world, we

00:26:51.510 --> 00:26:54.150
see a resurgence in
authoritarianism.

00:26:54.150 --> 00:26:56.850
New governments
emerging or governments

00:26:56.850 --> 00:27:01.260
transforming into increasingly
authoritarian regimes.

00:27:01.260 --> 00:27:03.810
And we think that
sending a signal

00:27:03.810 --> 00:27:05.880
through the successful
prosecution of one

00:27:05.880 --> 00:27:08.220
of the largest
unprosecuted war crimes

00:27:08.220 --> 00:27:11.960
will help us to challenge
that assumption of impunity.

00:27:11.960 --> 00:27:16.420
To say that we can be
light, like the young girl

00:27:16.420 --> 00:27:19.140
wrote, in the world
right now where

00:27:19.140 --> 00:27:22.720
we see setbacks in many
protections of human rights.

00:27:22.720 --> 00:27:25.380
We see setbacks in the
expansion of liberal democracy

00:27:25.380 --> 00:27:26.880
around the world.

00:27:26.880 --> 00:27:29.400
That we have to and we
have a responsibility

00:27:29.400 --> 00:27:33.720
to continue to
challenge impunity.

00:27:33.720 --> 00:27:36.570
Uphold standards
that we believe are

00:27:36.570 --> 00:27:39.720
the basis for the foundation
of peace and security

00:27:39.720 --> 00:27:40.390
in the world.

00:27:40.390 --> 00:27:42.340
And those standards,
we believe those

00:27:42.340 --> 00:27:44.440
to be that all people
are fundamentally

00:27:44.440 --> 00:27:46.000
equal in rights and dignity.

00:27:46.000 --> 00:27:48.550
And respect for
that principle is

00:27:48.550 --> 00:27:53.110
the basis of peace and
security across the world.

00:27:53.110 --> 00:27:54.190
I'm not making that up.

00:27:54.190 --> 00:27:56.020
It's what the World
War II generation

00:27:56.020 --> 00:27:59.970
signed into the Universal
Declaration of Human Rights.

00:27:59.970 --> 00:28:01.990
The generation
that suffered some

00:28:01.990 --> 00:28:04.300
of the worst atrocities
known in human history

00:28:04.300 --> 00:28:08.080
concluded that our peace,
that peace in the world,

00:28:08.080 --> 00:28:10.390
is linked to my
concern with how people

00:28:10.390 --> 00:28:12.040
are treated in my own country.

00:28:12.040 --> 00:28:16.120
But also how people are
treated in other countries.

00:28:16.120 --> 00:28:20.840
And so I think I'll conclude
my remarks there and maybe

00:28:20.840 --> 00:28:22.516
open it up to questions.

