00:31:52.550 --> 00:31:53.050
right.

00:31:56.270 --> 00:31:57.190
AUDIENCE: Hi.

00:31:57.190 --> 00:32:01.900
I have a question
about indirect support

00:32:01.900 --> 00:32:03.220
to neighboring countries.

00:32:03.220 --> 00:32:08.290
I hear that in Europe a lot of
politicians across the spectrum

00:32:08.290 --> 00:32:13.570
are trying to shift the
narrative regarding migration

00:32:13.570 --> 00:32:16.310
to advocate for supporting
countries in the region,

00:32:16.310 --> 00:32:19.150
especially to reduce
economic migration.

00:32:19.150 --> 00:32:22.240
And therefore shore up
the right of asylum.

00:32:22.240 --> 00:32:24.220
So we hear politicians
in Scandinavia

00:32:24.220 --> 00:32:27.310
who are pushing for
more support for Turkey.

00:32:27.310 --> 00:32:31.540
Or to have richer countries like
Saudi Arabia taking refugees.

00:32:31.540 --> 00:32:34.780
I'm wondering if you think
that the US can do anything

00:32:34.780 --> 00:32:39.370
given that immigration to the US
is really sensitive to provide

00:32:39.370 --> 00:32:42.370
better resources to Mexico,
Costa Rica, other countries

00:32:42.370 --> 00:32:43.270
in that region.

00:32:43.270 --> 00:32:45.070
Or if you think
that's an argument

00:32:45.070 --> 00:32:47.110
to deflect
responsibility to states

00:32:47.110 --> 00:32:52.540
that couldn't necessarily
handle the influx of refugees.

00:32:52.540 --> 00:32:54.670
NOAH BULLOCK: The issue
that you're touching on

00:32:54.670 --> 00:32:57.160
is called burden sharing.

00:32:57.160 --> 00:33:00.070
It's established in the
1951 Refugee Convention

00:33:00.070 --> 00:33:03.520
that no one state
should bear the burden

00:33:03.520 --> 00:33:05.870
of all refugees in the world.

00:33:05.870 --> 00:33:08.920
But the whole world
should bear that burden.

00:33:08.920 --> 00:33:13.690
And I think in the world
the overwhelming majorities

00:33:13.690 --> 00:33:18.070
of refugees are hosted by poor
and middle income countries.

00:33:18.070 --> 00:33:22.000
And what I said at the outset
of my presentation here,

00:33:22.000 --> 00:33:25.440
the United States is not
suffering an immigration crisis

00:33:25.440 --> 00:33:28.080
or a refugee crisis numerically.

00:33:28.080 --> 00:33:29.910
And Europe really isn't either.

00:33:29.910 --> 00:33:34.550
The largest numbers are in poor
and middle income countries.

00:33:34.550 --> 00:33:38.100
And so how do we
respond collectively

00:33:38.100 --> 00:33:41.940
to build capacity but
also share burden?

00:33:41.940 --> 00:33:44.130
And the way that the
international community

00:33:44.130 --> 00:33:47.610
is doing that is
through what they

00:33:47.610 --> 00:33:50.550
call a Global
Compact on refugees,

00:33:50.550 --> 00:33:58.810
but through new strategies to
externalize responsibility.

00:33:58.810 --> 00:34:00.480
So for example,
the United States

00:34:00.480 --> 00:34:03.730
supports Mexico with the
Southern Border Plan.

00:34:03.730 --> 00:34:07.350
It's this idea of extending
the border to the south

00:34:07.350 --> 00:34:11.219
to stop migrants
before they come,

00:34:11.219 --> 00:34:13.620
which can be seen as
a way of cutting off

00:34:13.620 --> 00:34:16.590
traditional access which
is at the border to refugee

00:34:16.590 --> 00:34:17.909
protection.

00:34:17.909 --> 00:34:22.650
There's a whole series of
actions, like you mentioned,

00:34:22.650 --> 00:34:26.100
that are trying to find ways
to skirt shared responsibility

00:34:26.100 --> 00:34:27.560
directly.

00:34:27.560 --> 00:34:32.699
And that tendency
also confronts what

00:34:32.699 --> 00:34:35.610
is the distinction between
a migrant and a refugee.

00:34:35.610 --> 00:34:38.580
Because what refugees are
doing around the world,

00:34:38.580 --> 00:34:41.679
they're behaving differently
than they used to.

00:34:41.679 --> 00:34:44.699
We have a refugee crisis because
the international community is

00:34:44.699 --> 00:34:47.280
incapable of ending conflict.

00:34:47.280 --> 00:34:50.670
So all conflicts keep going on.

00:34:50.670 --> 00:34:52.739
And new conflicts
become protracted.

00:34:52.739 --> 00:34:57.120
And so you have an accumulation
of displaced people.

00:34:57.120 --> 00:35:00.870
And the world is unable to
supply the humanitarian needs

00:35:00.870 --> 00:35:04.240
of those growing populations.

00:35:04.240 --> 00:35:06.600
And so what refugees are
doing is they're not--

00:35:06.600 --> 00:35:08.380
like in El Salvador
in the 1980s,

00:35:08.380 --> 00:35:11.010
many refugees crossed the
border and into Honduras

00:35:11.010 --> 00:35:13.680
and waited in refugee camps
for the conflict to end.

00:35:13.680 --> 00:35:15.660
And when it ended they returned.

00:35:15.660 --> 00:35:17.086
Today where refugees
are doing is,

00:35:17.086 --> 00:35:18.960
I'm not going to sit
around in a refugee camp

00:35:18.960 --> 00:35:20.640
and wait for them
to give me food

00:35:20.640 --> 00:35:22.890
because I don't think this
thing is ever going to end.

00:35:22.890 --> 00:35:24.090
And even if it
did, I don't think

00:35:24.090 --> 00:35:25.214
I'll be safe in my country.

00:35:25.214 --> 00:35:28.560
And so they enter into
a migratory routes.

00:35:28.560 --> 00:35:30.200
We call that mixed flows.

00:35:30.200 --> 00:35:32.400
And so the whole world is
trying to figure out who's

00:35:32.400 --> 00:35:34.170
a refugee, who's a migrant.

00:35:34.170 --> 00:35:35.550
What are the responsibilities?

00:35:35.550 --> 00:35:38.290
If one is a refugee
and one is a migrant,

00:35:38.290 --> 00:35:40.500
then it's all very complicated.

00:35:40.500 --> 00:35:42.600
The largest emerging
displacement crisis

00:35:42.600 --> 00:35:44.600
in the world is Venezuela.

00:35:44.600 --> 00:35:46.800
Possibly by next
year there'll be

00:35:46.800 --> 00:35:48.600
more people displaced
in Venezuela

00:35:48.600 --> 00:35:51.030
or something similar to
what you have in Syria.

00:35:51.030 --> 00:35:54.357
But there's no armed
conflict in Venezuela.

00:35:54.357 --> 00:35:56.190
And so all of the
countries in South America

00:35:56.190 --> 00:35:58.273
are saying we have a bunch
of Venezuelan migrants.

00:35:58.273 --> 00:35:59.460
We don't have refugees here.

00:36:02.820 --> 00:36:05.370
So there's sort of
a crisis, and we

00:36:05.370 --> 00:36:07.620
don't know how to
interpret what's happening.

00:36:07.620 --> 00:36:11.400
We're skirting
responsibilities collectively.

00:36:11.400 --> 00:36:16.680
And instead of trying to assume
responsibilities and generate

00:36:16.680 --> 00:36:19.980
a comprehensive humanitarian
response to displacement,

00:36:19.980 --> 00:36:23.430
end conflict, we're trying
to skirt responsibilities

00:36:23.430 --> 00:36:26.010
and externalize it to
countries of origin or host

00:36:26.010 --> 00:36:27.690
countries of refugees.

00:36:27.690 --> 00:36:30.540
Having said that, I
also think, for example,

00:36:30.540 --> 00:36:32.850
the bilateral support of
the United States government

00:36:32.850 --> 00:36:35.190
to the three countries
in the Northern Triangle

00:36:35.190 --> 00:36:39.870
to build protection
responses is important.

00:36:39.870 --> 00:36:41.974
I'll be in Washington
DC in October.

00:36:41.974 --> 00:36:43.890
And I'm going to take
the Supreme Court ruling

00:36:43.890 --> 00:36:45.690
and I'm going to
say to Congress,

00:36:45.690 --> 00:36:47.190
this is a roadmap for response.

00:36:47.190 --> 00:36:48.780
Support it.

00:36:48.780 --> 00:36:53.610
So I think that we have to
play both roles, assuming

00:36:53.610 --> 00:36:57.390
the responsibilities at home,
treating people with dignity

00:36:57.390 --> 00:37:00.930
and respect independent
of their condition.

00:37:00.930 --> 00:37:04.920
But also have solidarity
with countries of origin

00:37:04.920 --> 00:37:07.645
as they try and transform
those root causes.

00:37:07.645 --> 00:37:09.345
That was a long answer
to your question.

00:37:09.345 --> 00:37:11.540
But I could actually just
go on and on about it

00:37:11.540 --> 00:37:14.760
because it's the major
contentious issue

00:37:14.760 --> 00:37:17.970
in international
relations right now.

00:37:17.970 --> 00:37:20.460
It's just a big, big topic.

00:37:23.070 --> 00:37:26.360
AUDIENCE: I have a couple.

00:37:26.360 --> 00:37:30.410
Just to get back to your
specific example, so

00:37:30.410 --> 00:37:33.900
what was the outcome
for the family?

00:37:33.900 --> 00:37:36.930
NOAH BULLOCK: Yeah,
they left the country.

00:37:36.930 --> 00:37:38.640
All of them have
left the country

00:37:38.640 --> 00:37:42.750
and are in the process
of refugee resettlement

00:37:42.750 --> 00:37:45.010
somewhere else in the world.

00:37:45.010 --> 00:37:46.530
The last member to
leave the country

00:37:46.530 --> 00:37:49.230
was the father, the patriarch.

00:37:49.230 --> 00:37:52.200
And he stayed in the
country long enough

00:37:52.200 --> 00:37:55.290
to give testimony at
the Supreme Court.

00:37:55.290 --> 00:37:57.510
And it was a
powerful experience.

00:37:57.510 --> 00:37:59.550
Because it's not normal
for the Supreme Court

00:37:59.550 --> 00:38:03.300
to ask for those sort of
first-hand testimonies.

00:38:03.300 --> 00:38:06.420
And we did a lot of
witness prep with him

00:38:06.420 --> 00:38:11.680
prior to his interrogation
at the Court.

00:38:11.680 --> 00:38:14.520
And the guy, he did numbers.

00:38:14.520 --> 00:38:17.160
He did the numbers
about how much

00:38:17.160 --> 00:38:20.790
is in the security
budget of El Salvador.

00:38:20.790 --> 00:38:23.550
And he said, we as citizens
are paying all this money

00:38:23.550 --> 00:38:24.384
into security.

00:38:24.384 --> 00:38:25.800
And look, my whole
family is dead.

00:38:25.800 --> 00:38:26.710
I lost my house.

00:38:26.710 --> 00:38:27.640
I lost my livelihood.

00:38:27.640 --> 00:38:28.770
I lost my wife.

00:38:28.770 --> 00:38:32.640
So they owe me all
that money back.

00:38:32.640 --> 00:38:34.866
And we talked to him
about that not necessarily

00:38:34.866 --> 00:38:36.240
being the approach
that we should

00:38:36.240 --> 00:38:38.620
take in the Supreme Court.

00:38:38.620 --> 00:38:41.170
But he did an amazing job.

00:38:41.170 --> 00:38:44.840
You can imagine that there were
15 defense lawyers representing

00:38:44.840 --> 00:38:48.090
the highest officials in
the Salvadoran government.

00:38:48.090 --> 00:38:52.230
And his testimony,
he said, I was

00:38:52.230 --> 00:38:54.660
displaced by gangs at first.

00:38:54.660 --> 00:38:59.220
And when we sought help from
the government there was none.

00:38:59.220 --> 00:39:00.170
And I lost my home.

00:39:00.170 --> 00:39:02.520
I lost 25 years of mortgage.

00:39:02.520 --> 00:39:04.710
I lost my business.

00:39:04.710 --> 00:39:06.360
My family was dispersed.

00:39:06.360 --> 00:39:09.180
We lost all of our belongings.

00:39:09.180 --> 00:39:13.350
And then once we were in hiding
and hoping to find protection,

00:39:13.350 --> 00:39:14.910
and he turned and
looked directly

00:39:14.910 --> 00:39:17.400
at the defense attorney
for the Minister of Justice

00:39:17.400 --> 00:39:22.240
and Security and he
said, you killed my wife.

00:39:22.240 --> 00:39:24.915
And so it was a pretty
powerful moment.

00:39:24.915 --> 00:39:28.710
The Magistrates of the
Court, in open court

00:39:28.710 --> 00:39:31.770
recognizing executional
killings and procedural fraud

00:39:31.770 --> 00:39:35.890
in investigations
and serious issues.

00:39:35.890 --> 00:39:37.480
But he had the courage to do it.

00:39:37.480 --> 00:39:40.500
And when he was done,
we interviewed him

00:39:40.500 --> 00:39:42.960
and asked him how he
felt. And he just started

00:39:42.960 --> 00:39:45.980
crying tears of happiness.

00:39:45.980 --> 00:39:48.960
Something similar happens
with war crimes trials.

00:39:48.960 --> 00:39:53.910
When the survivors have given
testimony in court for so long,

00:39:53.910 --> 00:39:56.550
society has told them that
what happened to them is either

00:39:56.550 --> 00:40:01.110
their fault, they're criminals,
or it just didn't happen.

00:40:01.110 --> 00:40:03.810
And when they're able to
tell their story in front

00:40:03.810 --> 00:40:08.120
of the judicial authorities,
it's an important reparation

00:40:08.120 --> 00:40:11.700
to have society acknowledge
the terrible things

00:40:11.700 --> 00:40:14.560
that have happened to
you and acknowledge

00:40:14.560 --> 00:40:17.700
that those aren't
your fault. That's

00:40:17.700 --> 00:40:20.100
what happened to the family.

00:40:20.100 --> 00:40:22.530
AUDIENCE: Through your process
of one case, one family,

00:40:22.530 --> 00:40:27.480
one individual at a time, how
many cases, families, have

00:40:27.480 --> 00:40:31.030
Cristosal worked with and
helped in the period you've

00:40:31.030 --> 00:40:32.190
been with them?

00:40:32.190 --> 00:40:35.900
NOAH BULLOCK: Well, I can
remember case number one.

00:40:35.900 --> 00:40:39.990
Our first case-- we detected
this problem of displacement

00:40:39.990 --> 00:40:42.150
because we were
administering the High

00:40:42.150 --> 00:40:44.670
Commissioner for Refugees
program in El Salvador.

00:40:44.670 --> 00:40:47.220
So our mandate was
to assist people

00:40:47.220 --> 00:40:50.360
from other countries seeking
asylum in El Salvador, which

00:40:50.360 --> 00:40:53.160
were very few people.

00:40:53.160 --> 00:40:57.150
And Salvadorans began
to come to our office

00:40:57.150 --> 00:41:00.420
and trying to request asylum
which you can't do until you

00:41:00.420 --> 00:41:02.160
leave the country, right.

00:41:02.160 --> 00:41:05.310
But we got so many cases that we
decided that we should probably

00:41:05.310 --> 00:41:07.770
close this one
program down and begin

00:41:07.770 --> 00:41:11.250
to think about how we might
assist Salvadorans fleeing

00:41:11.250 --> 00:41:12.370
violence in the country.

00:41:12.370 --> 00:41:14.990
And we began to talk
around and trying

00:41:14.990 --> 00:41:17.640
to do advocacy
internally in the country

00:41:17.640 --> 00:41:19.740
and also externally
about the issue.

00:41:19.740 --> 00:41:21.990
But there was really
no context for anyone

00:41:21.990 --> 00:41:26.550
to understand it until the
child migrant crisis in 2014.

00:41:26.550 --> 00:41:28.740
But what I wanted
to say about that

00:41:28.740 --> 00:41:35.310
is that our first case was
a family of 25 people who

00:41:35.310 --> 00:41:38.370
were forced to flee
their homes and ended up

00:41:38.370 --> 00:41:41.270
camping outside the US embassy.

00:41:41.270 --> 00:41:45.510
When we heard about
that I said, oh man.

00:41:45.510 --> 00:41:47.490
We have to put our money
where our mouth is.

00:41:47.490 --> 00:41:50.340
And we had been planning
on building our protection

00:41:50.340 --> 00:41:52.350
responses and safe houses
and things like that.

00:41:52.350 --> 00:41:53.760
But we had no resources yet.

00:41:53.760 --> 00:41:56.560
We weren't ready for it.

00:41:56.560 --> 00:41:58.060
And I said to my
program director

00:41:58.060 --> 00:42:00.990
the embassy is going to call
us before 10:00 in the morning.

00:42:00.990 --> 00:42:02.520
I'm sure of it.

00:42:02.520 --> 00:42:05.910
So basically the
first case I spent

00:42:05.910 --> 00:42:08.010
the payroll for the
next month to try

00:42:08.010 --> 00:42:09.480
and activate our
first safe house.

00:42:09.480 --> 00:42:12.120
Literally from our
accountants all the way to

00:42:12.120 --> 00:42:15.510
are our tiny legal staff--
we were an organization

00:42:15.510 --> 00:42:17.190
of eight people at that point.

00:42:17.190 --> 00:42:20.010
We all took turns
operating the safe house.

00:42:20.010 --> 00:42:23.010
And that was case one.

00:42:23.010 --> 00:42:26.510
And now were on
case 450 something.

00:42:26.510 --> 00:42:31.140
So we've assisted thousands
of individual people.

00:42:31.140 --> 00:42:33.300
And now we're operating
in Guatemala and Honduras

00:42:33.300 --> 00:42:35.870
and beginning to see some of
the first results of our work

00:42:35.870 --> 00:42:38.400
there as well.

00:42:38.400 --> 00:42:40.660
This was case 91.

00:42:40.660 --> 00:42:43.070
AUDIENCE: One other question.

00:42:43.070 --> 00:42:47.960
The human rights-based approach
that Cristosal has adopted,

00:42:47.960 --> 00:42:50.916
can you explain that a little
bit in three or four minutes?

00:42:50.916 --> 00:42:51.740
NOAH BULLOCK: Yes.

00:42:51.740 --> 00:42:54.260
AUDIENCE: And where
the genesis of it,

00:42:54.260 --> 00:42:57.260
and how you're playing it?

00:42:57.260 --> 00:42:59.120
NOAH BULLOCK: Yeah,
I've used words

00:42:59.120 --> 00:43:03.480
that evoke a rights-based
approach, accountability,

00:43:03.480 --> 00:43:04.970
responsibility, the state.

00:43:09.050 --> 00:43:12.620
After World War II, the
international human rights

00:43:12.620 --> 00:43:14.480
resume was set up.

00:43:14.480 --> 00:43:17.460
It was set up on the basis
of a nation-state system.

00:43:17.460 --> 00:43:19.430
And the idea is
that a nation-state

00:43:19.430 --> 00:43:22.580
is the primary guarantor
of human rights,

00:43:22.580 --> 00:43:25.610
but also the primary
violator of human rights.

00:43:25.610 --> 00:43:31.010
And that means that it's
crime until the state fails

00:43:31.010 --> 00:43:32.750
to respond in a systematic way.

00:43:32.750 --> 00:43:35.270
And then it becomes
human rights violation.

00:43:35.270 --> 00:43:37.250
A murder is a murder.

00:43:37.250 --> 00:43:40.670
But the state's responsible for
investigating and prosecuting

00:43:40.670 --> 00:43:41.900
and protecting.

00:43:41.900 --> 00:43:46.460
States have to prevent, repair,
protect citizens, right.

00:43:46.460 --> 00:43:48.320
That's what they do.

00:43:48.320 --> 00:43:52.610
And so a rights-based
approach is this idea

00:43:52.610 --> 00:43:55.200
that there are people
who have rights.

00:43:55.200 --> 00:43:58.610
But then there are also
organizations and people

00:43:58.610 --> 00:44:00.710
who have corresponding duties.

00:44:00.710 --> 00:44:03.630
And so when we look at a problem
from a rights-based approach,

00:44:03.630 --> 00:44:07.520
we can't as an organization
substitute the people who have

00:44:07.520 --> 00:44:08.060
rights--

00:44:08.060 --> 00:44:09.950
in the case of the
victims, them-- and their

00:44:09.950 --> 00:44:12.190
processes of seeking justice.

00:44:12.190 --> 00:44:16.730
And we can't substitute the
state in their responsibilities

00:44:16.730 --> 00:44:18.650
to fulfill rights.

00:44:18.650 --> 00:44:20.870
So our actions have
to be empowering

00:44:20.870 --> 00:44:22.850
of both those parties.

00:44:22.850 --> 00:44:26.960
Meaning we have to empower the
victims to activate justice,

00:44:26.960 --> 00:44:31.200
to hold duty bearers or
the state accountable.

00:44:31.200 --> 00:44:33.740
But also we have to find
ways of strengthening

00:44:33.740 --> 00:44:36.530
the capacity of the
state to fulfill

00:44:36.530 --> 00:44:37.880
through positive actions.

00:44:37.880 --> 00:44:41.120
Like for example, in
El Salvador we just

00:44:41.120 --> 00:44:45.120
open a joint safe house with the
Women's Development Institute.

00:44:45.120 --> 00:44:47.510
And we're transferring
our knowledge and models

00:44:47.510 --> 00:44:50.780
of protecting families
to a state actor.

00:44:50.780 --> 00:44:53.240
But also, we have to
hold them accountable

00:44:53.240 --> 00:44:56.970
for systematic situations
of discrimination

00:44:56.970 --> 00:44:58.940
through actions like litigation.

00:44:58.940 --> 00:45:03.560
So what we can't do is
enter into the country

00:45:03.560 --> 00:45:08.810
and begin to substitute the
state by only assisting.

00:45:08.810 --> 00:45:10.827
That's the responsibility
of the state.

00:45:10.827 --> 00:45:12.410
What we're trying
to do is demonstrate

00:45:12.410 --> 00:45:16.730
how that could be done and then
activating the state to do it.

00:45:16.730 --> 00:45:18.800
So what's actually
worked out really strange

00:45:18.800 --> 00:45:20.570
with this whole case
of the litigation

00:45:20.570 --> 00:45:23.880
is through legal action
we created an obligation,

00:45:23.880 --> 00:45:25.460
a clear one on the state.

00:45:25.460 --> 00:45:28.700
Through the presentation
of new legislation,

00:45:28.700 --> 00:45:31.340
we've designed a
national response

00:45:31.340 --> 00:45:33.110
and organized how
the state is supposed

00:45:33.110 --> 00:45:35.840
to be responsible to victims.

00:45:35.840 --> 00:45:39.380
And in developing legal
models of assistance,

00:45:39.380 --> 00:45:42.140
humanitarian assistance,
psychosocial assistance we

00:45:42.140 --> 00:45:45.510
also can show the state
how they will respond.

00:45:45.510 --> 00:45:47.780
That's a rights-based approach.

00:45:47.780 --> 00:45:50.750
We've been able to assist
now thousands of people.

00:45:50.750 --> 00:45:53.720
But in doing that,
we've also demonstrated

00:45:53.720 --> 00:45:58.190
how nationally the
government could respond

00:45:58.190 --> 00:46:00.260
and created an
obligation to do it.

00:46:00.260 --> 00:46:04.430
It's a different way of working
than limiting your access

00:46:04.430 --> 00:46:07.670
to humanitarian assistance.

00:46:07.670 --> 00:46:10.160
AUDIENCE: So how do you
ensure that as you're

00:46:10.160 --> 00:46:12.770
going through the
process you are working

00:46:12.770 --> 00:46:14.660
not only with victims
and with the state,

00:46:14.660 --> 00:46:18.770
but also with diverse voices
who come from within the state

00:46:18.770 --> 00:46:22.100
and externally to create
a pathway for the state

00:46:22.100 --> 00:46:24.870
to operate with victims?

00:46:24.870 --> 00:46:27.230
NOAH BULLOCK: Yeah, you
can't only confront.

00:46:27.230 --> 00:46:29.060
You can't just be
confrontational, right.

00:46:29.060 --> 00:46:30.980
Otherwise you're
just on the outside

00:46:30.980 --> 00:46:35.200
screaming towards those
who hold power, right.

00:46:35.200 --> 00:46:36.960
You have to find
entry points and begin

00:46:36.960 --> 00:46:39.410
to work also cooperatively.

00:46:39.410 --> 00:46:41.600
So we've done that in
all three countries.

00:46:41.600 --> 00:46:44.750
In El Salvador, the
human rights ombudsman,

00:46:44.750 --> 00:46:47.630
which is a national
office for human rights,

00:46:47.630 --> 00:46:50.800
recognized forced displacement
I think about four years ago

00:46:50.800 --> 00:46:53.210
in a partnership
agreement with Cristosal.

00:46:53.210 --> 00:46:57.090
And we did assessments
with how they

00:46:57.090 --> 00:47:01.490
assist and drafted new
protocols and helped

00:47:01.490 --> 00:47:02.820
them to begin to respond.

00:47:02.820 --> 00:47:05.420
So they were the first state
institution to respond.

00:47:05.420 --> 00:47:07.870
And we've done that with the
public defender's office,

00:47:07.870 --> 00:47:10.610
with the Women's
Development Institute.

00:47:10.610 --> 00:47:13.030
We're working on that with
the Ministry of Health.

00:47:13.030 --> 00:47:14.780
So you have to find allies.

00:47:14.780 --> 00:47:15.890
The state is a big thing.

00:47:15.890 --> 00:47:17.960
It's not monolithic.

00:47:17.960 --> 00:47:20.120
And so you have to work
both that side, that more

00:47:20.120 --> 00:47:21.710
confrontation or
litigation side,

00:47:21.710 --> 00:47:25.410
to keep an obligation going.

00:47:25.410 --> 00:47:28.250
But also to work
cooperatively to show how

00:47:28.250 --> 00:47:32.160
response and strength and
capacities for fulfillment.

00:47:32.160 --> 00:47:36.770
So you're right that there
has to be that balance.

00:47:36.770 --> 00:47:38.960
And that means you
have to navigate

00:47:38.960 --> 00:47:44.000
tricky political
alliances sometimes.

00:47:44.000 --> 00:47:45.230
John, maybe one last thing.

00:47:45.230 --> 00:47:48.920
Before you leave, I just want to
call your attention to just one

00:47:48.920 --> 00:47:50.630
photo here.

00:47:50.630 --> 00:47:56.030
This one at the bottom, that's
a photo from the courtroom

00:47:56.030 --> 00:48:00.350
in Morazan where we're
prosecuting El Mozote war crime

00:48:00.350 --> 00:48:01.370
trial.

00:48:01.370 --> 00:48:06.440
In this day, this woman Rosario
was giving her testimony.

00:48:06.440 --> 00:48:09.320
She's a survivor
of the massacre.

00:48:09.320 --> 00:48:14.210
And this guy right here with
the gray hair and the glasses

00:48:14.210 --> 00:48:16.970
was responsible for the
Salvadorian Armed Forces

00:48:16.970 --> 00:48:19.050
in 1980.

00:48:19.050 --> 00:48:21.960
And he had to present
himself in court that day.

00:48:21.960 --> 00:48:25.190
And you can see this look
that she's giving him.

00:48:25.190 --> 00:48:28.680
I think that's another
example of the light, right.

00:48:28.680 --> 00:48:32.630
It's a really powerful
photo because she

00:48:32.630 --> 00:48:37.050
has had to wait 30 years
to be able to confront.

00:48:37.050 --> 00:48:38.210
Thank you, all.

